subject: RE: [Read_Alphabet] Quickscript in the NYTimes?
msgSnippet: Alex, That is cursive Hebrew.  Some cursive Hebrew letters have a very close resemblance to Quickscript, for instance Gimel looks so much like Kick, I think
messageBody:
Alex,

That is cursive Hebrew. Some cursive Hebrew letters have a very close
resemblance to Quickscript, for instance Gimel looks so much like Kick,
I think Read might have borrowed its shape consciously. (It isn't shown
in the example.) In the example, the letter that looks like QS Mime is
cursive Hebrew Ayin, and the one that looks like Roar is cursive Kaph.

jon

From: Alexander Lampros [mailto:lamproswc@...]
Sent: Thursday, August 19, 2004 10:59 AM
To: Read_Alphabet@yahoogroups.com
Subject: [Read_Alphabet] Quickscript in the NYTimes?


Go take a look at this link:
http://www.nytimes.com/2004/08/16/arts/music/16bump.html

The guy is holding up what sure looks like some sort
of quickscript. I realize its an Article about
Israel, but it doesn't look like Hebrew. Can anyone
more experienced than I read it?

Yours,

Alex
